Scenario
You are building a high-performance Video Streaming Platform. High-resolution video files (e.g., 4K, 5GB+) are extremely "expensive" to load into memory (RAM). If the system loads every video immediately upon startup, the application will crash or suffer from massive initial latency.

Your goal is to implement a system where video objects are created instantly as "placeholders," and the actual heavy resource loading only happens when the user clicks the Play button for the first time.

Requirements
Lazy Initialization (Proxy Pattern):

Create a VideoProxy that acts as a stand-in for the RealVideo.

The RealVideo object should not be instantiated until the play() method is called.

The Proxy must cache the RealVideo instance after the first load to prevent redundant disk operations on subsequent calls.

Abstraction of Creation (Factory Method Pattern):

Implement a VideoFactory to manage the creation logic.

The Client (Main) should not know whether it is receiving a Proxy or a Real object; it should only interact with the IVideo interface.

The Factory should have a protected/internal method specifically for the Proxy to request the "Real" object when needed.

Logging & Verification:

The Proxy should log whether it is creating a new instance or reusing an existing one from memory.